{"type":"message","id":"23b8e8db","parentId":"368fdb46","timestamp":"2026-05-02T15:45:55.505Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user didn't receive the email check results on Telegram. Looking at the run history:\n\nThe latest run (32c265b7) had:\n- status: \"ok\" (finished)\n- summary: \"I'll now execute the email processor skill step by step. First, let me check both inboxes simultaneously.\"\n- The output tokens were 18059 - that's a lot but the summary is very short. It seems like the model started but didn't finish.\n\nThe issue is that the run status shows \"ok\" but the summary is basically just the model's first response - it didn't actually complete the email processing. The model started reading the skill, took 309 seconds, but only output \"I'll now execute the email processor skill step by step. First, let me check both inboxes simultaneously.\" - that's a very minimal response.\n \nEven though the session has a delivery config for Telegram with announce mode, the messages weren't actually sent. The model just started executing but didn't finish sending the results to the user before the idle timeout kicked in.\n\nLooking at the actual output summary from the run, it's truncated - it says \"I'll now execute the email processor skill step by step. First, let me check both inboxes simultaneously\" - the model got cut off mid-execution and never completed the task.\n\nThe timing data is interesting: the successful runs with `fallbackUsed: false` (like the 82-second one) took a more direct path, while the failed ones used a fallback mechanism that attempted delivery but still didn't send the actual email messages to the user. So the system tried to deliver something, but the model didn't finish producing the actual email content.\n\nI should manually run the email check right now to show the user what the skill should actually output and confirm the messages are working.\n","thinkingSignature":"67c0fad7ba3ed9412786b