{"type":"message","id":"a0a21675","parentId":"3821189c","timestamp":"2026-05-02T16:20:11.576Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Since I reset the timestamp to now, all these unread emails from today will be considered \"new\". But many of these are older (from yesterday and earlier today). The timestamp is now 12:19 PM, so any email received before that will show as \"new\" even if they arrived hours ago.\n\nThe cron job at 12:05 PM reported \"50 unread emails\" - it must have processed all these same emails. But since the timestamp wasn't updated after that run (because the cron timed out before updating), I reset it. Now I'm picking up everything again.\n\nLet me just send Bobby what we have and explain the situation. Actually, since the cron at 12:05 PM reported it processed 50 unread and sent messages, and I reset the timestamp at 12:19 PM, I'm now re-reporting all these same emails again. \n\nI should set the timestamp to match when that 12:05 PM cron actually ran, so I'm not duplicating the same emails. Looking at the cron run details, it finished at 1777737952753 milliseconds, which converts to around 12:05 PM - that's when I should set the cutoff so I only get genuinely new emails after that point. ulas:\n- 1777737952753 ms / 1000 = 1777737952.753 seconds\n- Let me verify: 1777737952753 / 1000 = 1777737952.753, so 1777737952 seconds\n\nActually the ts in the cron run entry is the \"finished at\" timestamp in milliseconds. So:\n- Run started at: 1777737494817 ms\n- Run finished at: 1777737952753 ms\n- Duration: 457931 ms = ~457 seconds = ~7.6 minutes\n\nThe \"run at\" time was 1777737494817 ms = May 2, 2026 16:05:14 UTC = 12:05:14 PM EDT\n\nSo if I set the timestamp to 1777737494 (the start of the cron run), any email that came in during that run (between 12:05 and 12:12 roughly) will be picked up next time.\n\nActually, I just realized - the cron run summary said it found \"50 unread emails found\" and processed them. That means it already sent Bobby the messages for all these emails. The issue was that the timestamp wasn't updated because the cron timed out.\n\nSo now:\n1. I reset timestamp to 12:19 PM - this will cause ALL unread emails to be reported again on the NEXT run\n2. That means duplicate reports\n\nI need to set the timestamp back to the start of the cron run (12:05 PM = 1777737494) so the next cron run only picks up truly new emails since 12:05 PM. Otherwise I'm going to spam Bobby with all these emails again.\n","thinkingSignature":"a2e28f57dc1244480773f4dd2d9d86ce4df674b763c3a73b2711ffc26c5ce173"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_cvbcizwavu5o_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"echo 1777737494 > /Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-emmy/last_email_check.timestamp && echo \"Set timestamp to 12:05 PM ($(date -r 1777737494))\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":2009,"output":668,"cacheRead":93920,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":96597,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777738787593,"responseId":"064557236112aa3f050c07b80efa236b"}}
