{"type":"message","id":"7ff440b8","parentId":"36b4286d","timestamp":"2026-05-02T16:20:28.760Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So with the timestamp at 12:05 PM (1777737494):\n- TikTok (19de8d22cfadb367) - date: Sat, 02 May 2026 13:13:00 +0000 (UTC) = 9:13 AM EDT → NEW (after 12:05 PM)\n- Clipp.com (19de8915278a7aef) - date: Sat, 02 May 2026 12:02:10 +0000 (UTC) = 8:02 AM EDT → NOT new (before 12:05 PM)\n\nWait, 12:02 PM UTC would be 8:02 AM EDT. \n\nLet me recalculate this more carefully. UTC is 4 hours ahead of EDT, so when it's 12:02 PM UTC, that's 8:02 AM EDT. And when it's 1:13 PM UTC, that's 9:13 AM EDT. Both emails arrived before the 12:05 PM timestamp, so neither should be marked as new. But the email search shows they have unread status, which means they haven't been read yet since those timestamps.\n\nSo my earlier manual run that processed these emails around 12:40 PM should have marked them as read and updated the timestamp. Let me check what actually happened when I ran those commands.\n\nI sent myself two emails from TikTok and Clipp around 12:40 PM, which means the timestamp was updated to reflect that time. So when the cron runs next, it'll only pick up emails that arrived after that point. Since there haven't been any new emails since then, the cron won't find anything new—which is why you're not seeing those emails appear again.\n","thinkingSignature":"b8b5d5ea3f3459051321d19943f15f8cf1cde15b03099b433197430fb1937c27"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_zujtwubkk92y_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-emmy/last_email_check.timestamp && echo \"---\" && date -r $(cat /Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-emmy/last_email_check.timestamp)"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":169,"output":421,"cacheRead":96032,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":96622,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite