{"type":"message","id":"7f3489b1","parentId":"e33629fb","timestamp":"2026-05-02T17:07:45.783Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is saying that Gmail is showing emails that were already reported in previous runs. This means the timestamp comparison isn't working correctly - the skill is showing emails that arrived BEFORE the last check timestamp.\n\nThe issue is that the timestamp file was just updated to the current time (12:24 PM) during our one-shot check, so the next cron run won't find any \"new\" emails since everything will be before the current timestamp. But the user is seeing old emails being reported.\n\nWait, let me think about this again. The user said \"you are telling me about emails you have already told me about\" - this means the cron just ran and it's showing old emails again.\n\nThe problem might be:\n1. The timestamp is set to the current time (when we did the one-shot)\n2. The cron checks \"emails after this timestamp\" but all existing emails are older\n3. Unless new emails arrive between now and the cron run, there should be none\n\nBut wait - the cron ran and is reporting old emails. This means either:\n1. The timestamp wasn't properly updated after the last cron run\n2. The cron is not using the updated timestamp properly\n\nOR the user is seeing duplicates from the 12:05 PM run that I manually handled, and the messages the user didn't receive (due to Telegram issue) are being counted as \"already told\"\n\nActually, I think the issue is that the last cron run (at 12:05 PM) reported \"success\" (delivered: true) even though the user never received the messages. That run would have updated the timestamp. Then the user didn't get those messages, so from the user's perspective, they're now being told about emails they were never actually notified about.\n\nBut now the timestamp is set to 12:24 PM (current time) from our one-shot. So any emails older than that won't show as \"new\" in the next run.\n\nThe user is saying \"you are telling me about emails you have already told me about\" - this suggests the current cron run is showing duplicates. Let me re-read...\n\n\nI just manually sent the user an email summary of 49 unread emails. The timestamp was updated to 12:24 PM. The cron runs at 12:58 PM and will show emails newer than 12:24 PM - so any emails received between 12:24 and 12:58 PM would appear as new. But if the cron is showing emails from before 12:24 PM, then the timestamp either wasn't saved properly from the last cron run, or the cron run before that one was also broken and didn't update correctly.\n\nThe user might be seeing emails from our one-shot manual check, where I sent them everything as one combined message. But the cron should be sending separate messages for Gmail and iCloud. If the user is getting duplicate emails from the cron, it could be that the timestamp is stuck on an old value and the cron keeps re-reporting the same emails from the previous run. the last email check timestamp file to see what value is stored there, since that determines which emails get reported as new.\n","thinkingSignature":"342ebcdb916cd7feed28e208d7b5614f4bff51cc89166e17d379aa9eaa78e69a"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_cjhvsertd7hk_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-emmy/last_email_check.timestamp && echo \"---\" && date -r $(cat /Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-emmy/last_email_check.timestamp)"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":105573,"output":705,"cacheRead":320,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":106598,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777741632968,"responseId":"06456245d95280662814f3a12bb4674b"}}
