{"type":"message","id":"5128e3f1","parentId":"aa35f124","timestamp":"2026-05-02T17:08:10.795Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The timestamp was just updated to 13:03:42 which is basically right now. So the cron must have just run. But the issue is that emails from earlier today (like the TikTok 9:13 AM, Clipp 8:02 AM) are being reported again. That means either:\n\n1. The timestamp didn't properly track which emails were new vs old\n2. The filtering by date isn't working correctly\n\nThe issue might be that the skill compares the email's date (from the email header) against the timestamp file, but maybe the date format is confusing the model or the comparison isn't working right.\n\nOr alternatively, the emails that are being reported as \"new\" are actually UNREAD emails that were in the inbox from BEFORE the last timestamp, but the cron isn't properly filtering them out.\n\nWait - I think I see the issue. When I manually ran the email check earlier (at 12:24), I reset the timestamp to \"now\" (13:03:42), which means EVERYTHING in the inbox now looks \"new\" compared to that timestamp. The timestamp was reset to the moment I did the one-shot, not to when the last cron actually ran.\n\nLet me look at when the last cron actually ran vs when I did the manual one-shot.\n\nThe cron lastRanAtMs: 1777737494817 = 11:58 AM\nBut I reset the timestamp at 12:24 PM to 13:03:42 (basically \"now\")\n\nSo after my manual run, the timestamp file shows 13:03:42, meaning any email received before 13:03:42 looks \"new\" to the system. The cron that just ran at ~12:58 PM would have searched for emails newer than 13:03:42 but found none (because the timestamp is from the future almost), OR the cron ran with the old timestamp from before I reset it.\n\nActually wait - the timestamp was just updated to 13:03:42, which means the cron that just ran DID update it. \n\nThe cron probably ran around 12:58 PM with an earlier timestamp, so when it compared emails against that cutoff, it flagged the 9:13 AM TikTok and 8:02 AM Clipp emails as new since they came in after the last check. The timestamp file got overwritten during my manual run though, so I can't trace exactly what the cron was working with.\n\nThe real problem is that I'm resetting the timestamp to \"now\" when doing manual runs, which marks everything in the inbox as already reported. But the cron itself uses a sliding hourly window, not a fixed timestamp, so it's working differently than my manual checks.\n\nThe solution is to stop resetting the timestamp to the current time during manual runs. Instead, I should either leave it as-is or set it to match when the last cron actually ran. The system only cares about what the timestamp file says when the cron fires, not what time it is right now.\n","thinkingSignature":"724f151c680481deffab2380c379dc08367f00317f163f602a1531cfcdd639cf"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nI think I know what happened. Earlier when I did the one-shot manual check, I reset the timestamp file to \"now\" (13:03:42), which made EVERYTHING in your inbox look \"new\" to the system because it was newer than the timestamp.\n\nThen when the cron ran at 12:58 PM, it used that timestamp and reported all those old emails as \"new\" even though you already knew about them.\n\nLet me check the current state and fix it:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_lhid3bglx81l_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"echo $(date +%s) > /Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-emmy/last_email_check.timestamp && echo \"Reset timestamp to now: $(date)\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":143,"output":768,"cacheRead":105856,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":106767,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777741666037,"responseId":"064562628efb50b37b15e0e35bd05585"}}
