{"type":"message","id":"7a7b5372","parentId":"7c45407d","timestamp":"2026-05-02T17:11:02.249Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the issue! When Bobby said \"after:2026/05/02\" in the Gmail search, it showed emails from today (05-02). The two emails shown (TikTok at 09:13 UTC and Clipp at 08:02 UTC) are from this morning.\n\nBut wait - the `gog gmail get` output shows the TikTok email (19de8d22cfadb367) has date `Sat, 02 May 2026 13:13:00 +0000 (UTC)` which is in UTC. In EDT (Knoxville time, UTC-4), that would be 9:13 AM. \n\nAnd Clipp (19de8915278a7aef) has date `Sat, 02 May 2026 12:02:10 +0000 (UTC)` which is 8:02 AM EDT.\n\n\nSo these emails are from this morning, not after 1 PM. Bobby's check came back with \"I guess not\" because there genuinely aren't any new emails after 1 PM. But then why did the cron at 12:58 PM report those same old emails from this morning? The issue is that the timestamp comparison is comparing the wrong thing - the skill is checking the human-readable date instead of the actual internal timestamp, so old emails keep getting flagged as new. to the search results (which is shown as \"2026-05-02 09:13\" and \"2026-05-02 08:02\"). But if the model is comparing these dates incorrectly, it might be reporting them.\n\nActually, I think the real issue is simpler: the search `is:unread in:inbox` shows all unread emails, not just new ones. The model was supposed to filter by timestamp, but the cron at 12:58 PM reported these emails even though they arrived this morning. So either the timestamp comparison wasn't working right, or the model was just reporting ALL unread emails regardless.\n\nLooking at the dates more carefully - the TikTok email arrived at 13:13 UTC (9:13 AM EDT) and Clipp at 12:02 UTC (8:02 AM EDT). If the cron at 12:58 PM EDT was using timestamp 1777741422, that converts to 1:03 PM EDT today. I need to figure out what the actual timestamp comparison logic should be checking.\n\nThe issue is that the `date` field in the email header shows \"Sat, 02 May 2026 13:13:00 +0000 (UTC)\" - this is the human-readable date header, not the Unix epoch timestamp. The actual internal timestamp that Gmail uses for filtering is much larger (like 1777737494 or 1777705115), but I don't have direct access to it from the gog output. When the cron ran at 12:58 PM, it reported the TikTok and Clipp emails even though they were from earlier today, which suggests the timestamp check wasn't filtering them out correctly. So the cron at 12:58 PM reported those two emails despite them arriving hours earlier. The timestamp file shows 13:03:42 EDT, which would match 1777741422 — but the cron run itself happened at 12:58 PM. I'm realizing the cron fires every hour from the anchor point 1773961081922 (ms), so I need to figure out where 12:58 PM actually falls in that sequence and why it would report emails from this morning when they're definitely older than the current timestamp.\n","thinkingSignature":"d9a808fbbceddf4db1f72b74fbba422e71413c5127d2852f7ec7a51bf8e3c9b0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_znyqup0qy7h7_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nts = 1777741422\nimport datetime\ndt = datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(ts)\nprint(f'Last timestamp: {ts} = {dt}')\nprint(f'Now: {datetime.datetime.now()}')\n# Email dates\nemails = {\n    'TikTok': 'Sat, 02 May 2026 13:13:00 +0000',\n    'Clipp': 'Sat, 02 May 2026 12:02:10 +0000',\n}\nimport email.utils\nfor name, raw in emails.items():\n    dt = email.utils.parsedate_to_datetime(raw)\n    print(f'{name}: {dt} UTC -> {dt.astimezone()} EDT = epoch {int(dt.timestamp())}')\n\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":308,"output":910,"cacheRead":108000,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":109218,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777741844537,"responseId":"064563144d84a6c41cb4c02769274d44"