{"type":"message","id":"81508fb0","parentId":"453e555e","timestamp":"2026-05-02T17:11:14.287Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Ah, now I see the issue! The email dates are in UTC:\n- TikTok email: 13:13 UTC = 09:13 EDT\n- Clipp: 12:02 UTC = 08:02 EDT\n\nBut the last timestamp was set at 13:03 EDT (1777741422). So the comparison should work correctly because the timestamps are being compared properly.\n\nWait, but the issue is that when I reset the timestamp, it went to 13:08 EDT (now). The emails that arrived today are:\n- TikTok: 09:13 EDT (before the reset, would be new)\n- Clipp: 08:02 EDT (before the reset, would be new)\n\n\nBut I'm also noticing the model might be comparing the human-readable date string instead of the Unix epoch. In step 4 of the skill, it says \"Check if `date > last_check`\" — the date field from Gmail output looks like \"Sat, 02 May 2026 13:13:00 +0000 (UTC)\" which converts to 09:13 EDT, but the Unix epoch for that timestamp is 1777727580. I need to figure out what the actual internalDate field is in Gmail and whether the comparison is using the right value.\n\nLooking at the logs, one of the messages was sent at 11:16 EDT but the email timestamp is from 09:13 EDT — meaning the email arrived before I even reported it, which shouldn't be possible if I'm checking timestamps correctly.\n\nLet me trace through the timestamps more carefully. The message IDs show a clear sequence: the last timestamp was set at 13:03 EDT during the morning cron run, but an email with ID 19de8d22cfadb367 arrived at 09:13 EDT that same morning. So when the cron runs again at 12:58 PM, it would compare the current timestamp against the email's internal date to determine if it's new. The issue is that the last successful run was at 12:58 PM, not 1:03 PM, which means the timestamp wasn't actually updated at that time. This explains why the 1 PM run still showed old emails—the timestamp remained at 11:58 AM from the earlier reset.\n\nThen at 1:08 PM Bobby reset the timestamp to the current time, so the next cron run at 1:58 PM will catch only emails arriving after that point. For the emails I'm seeing now, there's nothing newer than 1 PM today since the search shows the most recent ones are from 9:13 AM and 8:02 AM, both before the current timestamp of 1:08 PM.\n\nLet me verify those timestamps to make sure I'm reading the conversion correctly.\n","thinkingSignature":"1e42676853229e09c910f5938330fe3507a5e7d32958b3151a04df83094df3df"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_4694mdlmy29h_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport email.utils, datetime\n# Current timestamp\nts = 1777741422\nlast_dt = datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(ts)\nprint(f'Last timestamp: {last_dt} EDT')\n\n# Email dates from gog output\nemails = [\n    ('TikTok', 'Sat, 02 May 2026 13:13:00 +0000'),\n    ('Clipp', 'Sat, 02 May 2026 12:02:10 +0000'),\n]\nfor name, raw in emails:\n    dt = email.utils.parsedate_to_datetime(raw)\n    print(f'{name}: {dt} UTC')\n\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":349,"output":721,"cacheRead":108288,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":109358,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777741862335,"responseId":"06456326d7c9fd62f5922e713adaf44a"}}
