{"type":"message","id":"81565a12","parentId":"ac86a235","timestamp":"2026-05-02T18:17:30.700Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So Bobby wants the email check to cover the past hour, not \"since the last run.\" If the cron fires at 2pm, it should check for emails received between 1pm and 2pm.\n\nCurrently the cron fires every hour at :59 (1:59, 2:59, etc.) and uses the timestamp file to track \"emails since last run\". But the timestamp gets updated to the current time when the cron runs, so the next run looks from that time forward.\n\nWhat Bobby wants:\n- At 2pm, check for emails from 1pm-2pm (the past hour)\n- At 3pm, check for emails from 2pm-3pm (the past hour)\n  \nThe problem is the current logic uses the timestamp to track \"emails AFTER this time\" rather than \"emails in the last hour before this time\". To fix this, the skill should set the timestamp to (current time - 1 hour) as the lower bound, then search for emails between that time and now, and update the timestamp to current time for the next run.\n\nActually, I need to think through the timestamp behavior more carefully. The timestamp file holds an epoch time, and when the cron runs at 2pm, it uses that stored epoch to determine the search window. The issue is that after a successful run, the timestamp gets updated to the current time, so the next run at 3pm would search for emails after 3pm, missing the 2pm-3pm window entirely.\n\nThe fix is to use a sliding window approach: at each cron run, set LAST_CHECK to (current time - 1 hour), and search for emails between LAST_CHECK and now. This way, if no new emails arrive, the timestamp gets updated to the current time, but on the next run we'd still be searching the same window, which could cause duplicates if emails are found.\n\nThe core issue is that the timestamp represents the lower bound of the search window, not a fixed point. If I update it to NOW after each run and then subtract 1 hour at the next run, I'm effectively searching the same period twice. I need a different strategy—perhaps storing the start time of the current hour or using a fixed window that doesn't depend on the previous run's timestamp.\n\nLet me think about what Bobby actually wants: at 2pm, check for emails from 1pm-2pm. At 3pm, check for emails from 2pm-3pm. This means the timestamp should represent the START of the current hour, not the time of the last check. So when the cron runs at 2pm, I'd set the window to [1pm, 2pm), mark those emails as read, and update the timestamp to 2pm for the next run. But wait—if I'm searching for emails before 2pm and updating the timestamp to 2pm, then on the next run at 3pm, the search would look for emails after 2pm, which is correct. However, I need to make sure I'm not re-processing emails that were already handled in the previous cycle.\n\nThe real issue is that this approach doesn't properly track which emails have been seen. I should store the timestamp of the most recently processed email instead, so at 2pm I'd find all emails received after the last timestamp (around 1pm), report them, then update to the latest one. That way on the next run at 3pm, I'm only looking at emails that arrived after 2pm.\n\nThe problem is that \"no new emails\" could mean either there were genuinely none, or there were some but they weren't processed. If the timestamp keeps getting updated to the current time even when nothing new arrived, then the next check window shrinks and I might miss emails. I need to verify that the timestamp is only updated when actual new emails were found and reported. If no new emails arrive between 1pm and 2pm, the timestamp stays at 1777704000. Then at 2pm, I'd search for emails after 1777704000 and find none, and again skip updating the timestamp. So the timestamp would remain at 1777704000 even after multiple empty runs. That's the problem — if the cron checks every hour and finds nothing, it never advances the timestamp, so the next check is still looking from the same point. This means if an email arrives at 2:30pm during the 3pm check, it would be caught, but I'd have missed the 2pm check window.\n\nBut wait, that's not quite right either. At 2pm, if there's no email, I skip the update. Then at 3pm, I search after 1777704000 and find the 2:30pm email, reporting it as \"new\". So it does get caught, just one hour late.\n\nThe real issue is that I'm not reporting it immediately when it arrives. That's the core problem I'm trying to solve.\n\nThe current flow is: cron fires at 2pm, finds nothing, skips the update. Cron fires again at 3pm, finds the 2:30pm email, reports it. By then it's been sitting for 30 minutes. Bobby wants it reported as soon as possible, ideally within minutes of arrival.\n\nThe most practical fix would be to run the cron more frequently—every 15 or 30 minutes instead of hourly. That way, even if an email arrives just after a check, it would be caught within 15-30 minutes rather than potentially waiting nearly an hour. Alternatively, I could tweak the logic so that at 2pm the search window covers emails from 1pm-2pm (using now-1h as the start), report them, then update the timestamp to 2pm so the next run checks from 2pm onward. emails from 1pm-2pm. Then at 3pm, it checks emails from 2pm-3pm.\n\nThe current code uses `date +%s` which gives Unix epoch. But the issue is whether the email dates from gog are being compared correctly as Unix epochs. Let me verify.\n\nWhen cron fires at 2pm EDT, current epoch is ~1777744800. last_check = current epoch - 3600 = ~1777741200. Search for emails with date > last_check. All emails from 1pm-2pm would have epoch > 1777741200. Those from before 1pm would have epoch < 1777741200 and be skipped.\n\nBut if no emails are found at 2pm, the timestamp doesn't get updated. So at 3pm, last_check is still 1777741200 (1pm), and it would find all emails from 1pm-3pm instead of just 2pm-3pm. That's the bug—the timestamp should be updated even when no emails are found, so the next check only looks at the following hour's emails. If the cron fires at 2pm and finds no new emails, the timestamp remains at 1pm. Then at 3pm, when last_check is still 1pm, I'd search for all emails since then—getting both the 2:30pm email and anything from before 1pm, which breaks the hourly window. The current approach keeps last_check anchored to the previous run's time, but I need to reconsider how the timestamp should be updated after each cycle to maintain the correct window. , you should search for emails from (now-1h) to now and update the timestamp to now regardless of whether emails were found.\n\nActually, the simplest fix is to change step 10 to unconditionally update the timestamp to current time every run, not just when new emails are found. This way at 2pm you'd search 1pm-2pm, and at 3pm you'd search 2pm-3pm, which is exactly what we want.\n\nThe only downside is if an email arrives at 2:55pm and the cron runs at 3pm, the search window would be 2pm-3pm and would catch it. So the logic is sound—I just need to make the timestamp update unconditional rather than conditional on whether new emails were found.\n","thinkingSignature":"dc680df28c5541a5ca0893127642a90be15695e579b32a49d322558d131c78e0"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_049xdupu9u7f_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"echo $(date +%s) > /Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-emmy/last_email_check.timestamp && echo \"Reset to: $(date)\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":110251,"output":1744,"cacheRead":192,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":112187,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777745796548,"responseId":"0645728589fc8388fce09f7a7700ee35"}}
